Setting UP JPA Connection:

1. Adding Dependencies
a. Maven
Add the following to your pom.xml:

xml

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-data-jpa</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>
    <artifactId>h2</artifactId>
    <scope>runtime</scope>
</dependency>

spring-boot-starter-data-jpa: Includes Spring Data JPA, Hibernate, and all required dependencies.
h2: In-memory database for development/testing. Replace with your DB (e.g., MySQL, PostgreSQL)
in production.

2. Configuring Database Connection
You can use either application.properties or application.yml in src/main/resources.

a. application.properties
Example:

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:h2:mem:testdb
spring.datasource.driver-class-name=org.h2.Driver
spring.datasource.username=sa
spring.datasource.password=
spring.jpa.database-platform=org.hibernate.dialect.H2Dialect

# Optional: Show SQL in console
spring.jpa.show-sql=true
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update
Key Properties:

spring.datasource.url: JDBC URL for your database.
spring.datasource.driver-class-name: Database driver.
spring.datasource.username/password: Credentials.
spring.jpa.database-platform: Hibernate dialect for your DB.
spring.jpa.show-sql: Show SQL queries in logs.
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto: Auto-create/update tables (update, create, validate, none).


How to Get the JDBC URL:

1. Check Your Database Type
Each database has its own JDBC URL format. Here are some common examples:

H2 (In-Memory Database):

properties

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:h2:mem:testdb
mem:testdb means an in-memory database named testdb.

MySQL:

properties

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydatabase
localhost: Database server address (use your server’s IP or hostname if remote).
3306: Default MySQL port.
mydatabase: Your database name.

PostgreSQL:

properties

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/mydatabase
5432: Default PostgreSQL port.

SQL Server:

properties

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:sqlserver://localhost:1433;databaseName=mydatabase

2. How to Find Your Database Name, Host, and Port:

Database Name: The name you gave your database when you created it.
Host: The server where your database is running (often localhost for local development).
Port: The port your database server is listening on (default ports: MySQL - 3306, PostgreSQL
- 5432, SQL Server - 1433).

3. Setting Up DataSource, EntityManagerFactory, and TransactionManager

a. What Are These?

DataSource:
Manages the database connection pool.
Spring Boot auto-configures it based on your properties.

EntityManagerFactory:
Creates EntityManager instances, which handle persistence operations (CRUD).
Spring Boot auto-configures it using JPA settings.

TransactionManager:
Manages transactions (commit/rollback).
Spring Boot auto-configures a JpaTransactionManager for JPA.

b. How Spring Boot Handles Configuration?

You usually don’t need to configure these beans manually.
Spring Boot auto-configures them if you have the right dependencies and properties.